        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": "Ceiling height determines proper down rod length to position fan blades at optimal height for maximum air circulation and safety. The ideal fan blade height is 8-9 feet from floor, providing best air circulation while maintaining safe clearance. Down rod selection by ceiling height: 8 feet or lower ceilings: Flush-mount or hugger-style fans (no down rod)—Mounts motor housing directly against ceiling, suitable only for standard 8-foot ceilings. Provides minimum 7-foot blade clearance. Not recommended for rooms with ceiling fans due to reduced air circulation efficiency. 8 to 9 foot ceilings: 3-6 inch down rods (standard)—Short down rods position blades at optimal 8-9 foot height while maintaining adequate ceiling clearance for motor cooling. Most common installation configuration for typical Tucson homes. 9 to 10 foot ceilings: 6-12 inch down rods—Medium down rods maintain 8-9 foot blade height from higher ceilings. Improves air circulation compared to flush-mount while preserving visual aesthetics. 10 to 12 foot ceilings: 12-24 inch down rods—Longer down rods required to bring blades down to optimal height for living spaces. Particularly important in rooms with 10+ foot ceilings where flush-mount fans would provide minimal air circulation at occupant level. 12 to 16 foot ceilings (vaulted great rooms, two-story entryways): 24-48 inch down rods—Extended down rods essential for proper blade positioning in tall spaces. Often requires specialized angled mounting for sloped ceilings. 16+ foot ceilings (dramatic two-story great rooms, commercial): 48-72 inch down rods OR commercial-grade extended systems—Extremely long down rods or specialized mounting systems for cathedral ceilings and exceptional ceiling heights. Requires professional installation with proper structural support and balancing."
