        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": "For large or irregularly-shaped rooms, homeowners face the decision: install one very large ceiling fan or multiple properly-sized fans? Our experience indicates multiple fans typically provide superior performance: Two 52-inch fans in a 20x20 great room provide better air circulation than one 72-inch fan, eliminate dead zones in room corners and edges, allow independent speed control for different room areas, distribute air more evenly throughout the space, and provide redundancy if one fan fails. Multiple fan strategy works best for: L-shaped combined living/dining rooms, long rectangular rooms (length exceeds width by 2:1 or more), open-concept spaces combining multiple functional areas, rooms with obstacles dividing space (columns, partial walls, large furniture groupings), and outdoor covered patios where different areas have different airflow needs. Single large fan makes sense for: Perfectly square or slightly rectangular rooms, rooms under 400 sq ft, locations where ceiling access limits fan placement options, budget constraints limiting number of fans installed, and situations where one centrally-located fan provides complete coverage. Our electricians assess your specific room layout during site consultation and recommend the optimal fan configuration for your space, whether that's one large fan, multiple fans, or a combination approach."
