        "content": "Traditional bedroom fan placement centers the fan in the room for even air distribution. However, master bedrooms often benefit from alternative placement strategies. Centered placement (traditional): Best for: Symmetrical bedrooms, rooms under 250 sq ft, bedrooms with centered bed placement. Advantages: Even air distribution throughout room, simple installation (often existing ceiling box at room center), aesthetically balanced appearance. Disadvantages: Direct airflow over bed may feel uncomfortable for some sleepers, may conflict with centered light fixture needs. Off-center placement over bed: Best for: Large master bedrooms (250+ sq ft), rooms with bed against wall (not centered), bedrooms requiring separate ceiling light fixture. Advantages: Direct airflow over bed optimizes sleeping comfort, allows separate ceiling light at room center, places fan where it provides most benefit. Disadvantages: May create slight air circulation imbalance in room corners, requires new wiring and electrical box installation if no existing box at desired location. Dual fan strategy for large masters: For master bedrooms exceeding 350 sq ft, consider two ceiling fans: One centered over bed area (primary cooling), one in sitting area or over seating (secondary circulation). This dual approach eliminates dead zones, provides independent speed control for different room areas, and ensures comprehensive air circulation throughout large master suites. Our electricians assess your bedroom layout during consultation and recommend optimal fan placement based on room dimensions, bed location, existing wiring, and personal comfort preferences."
