        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": "NEC and fan manufacturer safety standards require specific clearances preventing blade strikes, ensuring adequate air circulation, and maintaining safe operation: Blade-to-floor clearance (minimum 7 feet, 8 feet preferred): NEC requires minimum 7-foot clearance from floor to lowest point of fan blades in all occupied spaces. We recommend 8-foot minimum for high-traffic areas, dining rooms, and bedrooms to prevent head strikes. Ceiling fans in garages, workshops, or storage areas may use 7-foot minimum if appropriate for space use. Down rod length selection must account for ceiling height, ensuring proper blade height while maintaining this critical safety clearance. Blade-to-ceiling clearance (minimum 10-12 inches): Adequate blade-to-ceiling clearance ensures proper air circulation and motor cooling. Minimum 10 inches from ceiling to top of blade brackets required for efficient airflow. 12-14 inches preferred for optimal performance (requires down rod even on standard 8-9 foot ceilings). Flush-mount fans eliminate this clearance—acceptable for 8-foot ceilings but reduces efficiency 15-25% compared to down rod mounting. Blade-to-wall clearance (minimum 18 inches): Fan blades must maintain 18-inch minimum clearance from walls and vertical obstructions (columns, posts). This clearance prevents air turbulence creating noise, vibration, and reduced efficiency. Ceiling fans too close to walls create uncomfortable drafts and annoying turbulence sounds. Room size determines appropriate fan blade span—undersized rooms cannot accommodate large fans while maintaining safe clearances. Blade-to-obstruction clearance (case-by-case requirements): Ceiling-mounted light fixtures, smoke detectors, recessed lights, ceiling beams, and other obstructions require adequate clearance preventing blade strikes. General rule: 24-inch minimum clearance from any obstruction fan blades might contact during operation or installation. Our electricians carefully measure and verify all clearances during site assessment, recommending appropriate fan sizes and down rod lengths ensuring code-compliant, safe installation."
