        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": "This cannot be overstated: Ceiling fans MUST be mounted to fan-rated electrical boxes. Standard light fixture electrical boxes are not designed for fan weight and dynamic forces, creating catastrophic failure risk. Why fan-rated boxes are mandatory: Ceiling fans create dynamic rotational forces standard boxes cannot withstand. Fan weight (15-50 pounds) plus rotational forces can exceed 200 pounds of stress on mounting points. Standard light fixture boxes are rated for 50 pounds maximum static load—inadequate for fan applications. Fan-rated boxes are specifically designed and tested for 70+ pounds dynamic load with rotation and vibration. Ceiling fan failures due to inadequate boxes have caused serious injuries and property damage—hence the strict code requirements. Identifying fan-rated boxes: All fan-rated boxes include clear labeling: 'Acceptable for Fan Support' or 'Listed for Ceiling Fan Support' or similar language. Typically heavier construction with reinforced mounting ears and larger mounting screws. Must be securely attached to ceiling joist or blocking (not just to drywall with toggle bolts). Retrofit fan-rated box installation: For locations without existing fan-rated boxes, we install appropriate solutions: Attic-accessible ceilings: Install new fan-rated box attached directly to ceiling joist or add blocking between joists for mounting. Vaulted ceilings without attic access: Use retrofit fan-rated boxes (expanding brackets attach to ceiling joists through ceiling opening). Concrete ceilings: Specialized mounting systems with concrete anchors rated for fan support. Our installation process always includes fan-rated box verification or installation—non-negotiable for safety and code compliance. We refuse to install ceiling fans on inadequate boxes, protecting homeowners from dangerous liability."
